<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="approximate">@HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}}</a> is used to indicate an approximate amount or an approximate maximum.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come^month}}ha,@KJ{{one^week^interval}}@EM{{hodo}}@KJ{{nine^state}}he@KJ{{exit^lengthen}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Next month I'll be going on a business trip to Kyushu for as long as a week.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<br/><br/>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^degrees}}no@KJ{{matter^happenstance}}de,100@KJ{{person}}@EM{{hodo}}no@KJ{{person}}ga
      @KJ{{death}}ndasoudesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I heard that some 100 people died in this accident.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="comparison">@HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}}</a> is used to indicate a comparison. Note that when @HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}}
follows a noun, the predicate must be in the negative.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^year}}ha@KJ{{gone^year}}@EM{{hodo}}@KJ{{cold}}kunaidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This year is not as cold as last year.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="extent">@HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}}</a> indicates the extent of an action or condition by citing a specific example.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^day}}ha,@KJ{{exertion^study}}gadekinai@EM{{hodo}}@KJ{{tired}}reta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Today I'm so tired that I cannot study.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="example">The</a> same idea can be expressed with a slightly different sentence pattern.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{supo-tsu}}noatoni@KJ{{drink}}mu@KT{{bi-ru}}@EM{{hodo}}oishiimono@EM{{hanai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There is nothing as good as a beer drunk after sport.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="extreme">@HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}}</a> can be used to give an extreme example.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KT{{kare-}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{tears}}:namida}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{exit}}:de}}ru@EM{{hodo}}@FG{{@KJ{{spicy}}:kara}}i.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This curry is eye-wateringly hot.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="about">When</a> @HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}} is used with a quantifier, it means "about".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{bi-ru}}wo@KJ{{three^book}}@EM{{hodo}}@KJ{{drink}}mimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I drank about three bottles of beer.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="adverbial-positive">With</a>  a positive predicate, when @HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}} is modified by a verb or adjective, it can form an adverbial clause with the meaning "so ... that".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{cry}}:na}}ketekisouna@EM{{hodo}}@FG{{@KJ{{emotion^move}}:kandou}}shita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I was moved so deeply that I almost cried.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{transmit^overall^bull's*eye}}:dentouteki}}namonoha,@FG{{@KJ{{old}}:furu}}i@EM{{hodo}}@FG{{@KJ{{value^price}}:kachi}}gaaru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Traditional items have more value if they are older.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="adverbial-negative">With</a>a negative predicate, when @HI{{@EM{{hodo}}}} is modified by a verb or adjective, it can form an adverbial clause with the meaning "not as ... as".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{shikashi,soreha@FG{{@KJ{{mouth}}:kuchi}}de@KJ{{say}}u@EM{{hodo}}@FG{{@KJ{{simplicity^simple}}:kantan}}nakotodehanai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      [context:Making clothes that customers buy regardless of price]</br>
      However, that's easier said than done.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

